1. Introduction 
===============
   mmSAP s SAP (Slight atari player) player based on ASAP library that uses ALSA for audio output
   and has GTK+ 3.0 based GUI

   SAP is a special file format designed to store POKEY-based Atari XL/XE music.
   The biggest collection of such music is ASMA (Atari SAP Music Archive) that
   can be found at: http://asma.atari.org.

   ASAP library also allows you to load RMT,TMC,TM2,MPT,CMC files directly. For fresh
   information about supported formats, refer to the ASAP project.

   mmSAP tries to be the best specialized player that takes into account all
   features of the SAP file format.

2. Features
===========

   * Based on ASAP library (http://asap.sourceforge.net/) that provides precise
     and high fidelity POKEY emulation
   * Easy to use GTK+ 3.0 based user interface
   * Fully featured playlist
   * Configurable POKEY visualization
   * Good support for ASMA STIL
   * Four repeat modes (stand still after subsong,repeat subsong,repeat tune,repeat playlist)
   * Seeking inside subsongs that have TIME tag
   * Single instance application (using GTK+ 3.0 features)
   * Drag and drop support
   * 'Browse and play' file chooser
   * Audio output through ALSA
   * Possibility to mute selected POKEY channels

2. Operating systems supported
==============================
   Modern GNU/Linux distributions.
   There is no support for Microsoft Windows (and it is not planned).

3. Dependencies
===============
   * gtkmm 3.0, GTK+ 3.0, just install runtime and development libraries
   * ALSA 1.0.X, just install alsa-devel package.
   * ASAP 3.0.0 or newer, download from http://asap.sourceforge.net/. Latest release is recommended.
   * D-Bus
   * pkg-config
   * CMake
   * GCC

4. Compiling and installing
===========================

   ASAP 3.0.0 and newer
   ------------------------------
   
   * All you need to install is ASAP library (libasap)
   * Extract the tarball and change working directory to the extracted one.
     Invoke following commands:
     
     make lib
     # become super user
     make install-lib
   
   If you are in doubt, consult ASAP documentation.

   mmSAP instalation
   -------------------

   * Change working directory to the directory that contains mmSAP  
     sources and invoke following commands: 
     cmake .
     make
     #become super user
     make install

   * The ${HOME}/.config directory must exist, in other
     case mmSAP will not be able to save the preferences.
     This directory usually exists (GTK+ uses it and mmSAP
     uses GTK+)

5. Modifying GUI
================
   * Use Glade 3.10.0 or newer to modify mmsap.ui. 

   * GUI is linked into binary. To convert mmsap.ui to C
     array, you can use for example KHexEdit or its successor 
     called Okteta or something similar.

6. Planning:
============
   Bugfixes, new features

7. Tested GNU/Linux distributions
========================================
   openSuSE 12.1, Ubuntu 12.04, Kubuntu 12.04

8. Problems with SAP tunes
==============================
   If you encounter problem with specific SAP tune, first
   try it with asap2wav and play back the generated WAVE
   file. If the problem persists, the problem is not
   mmSAP related.

9. Known problems
=================
   * Seeking does not work with tunes that lack TIME tag. This
     probably won't be fixed

   * Seeking works with almost all tunes from ASMA, but not
     with all

